s of procedural justice by police. In this book, Robert E. Worden and Sarah J. McLean argue that the procedural justice model of reform is a mirage. From a distance, procedural justice seemingly offers a relief from strained police-community relations. But a closer look at police organizations and police-citizen interactions shows that the relief offered by such reform is, in fact, illusory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aPolice administrationzUnited States. 0aPolice-community relationszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aaccountability.  aamerican citizens.  aamerican police.  acitizens and police.  acitizens.  acops.  adecision making.  ajustice system.  alaw and order.  alaw enforcement.  alegal issues.  apolice action.  apolice department.  apolice legitimacy.  apolice procedure.  apolice reform.  apolice system.  apolicing.  aprocedural justice model.  aprocedural justice.  areformation.  asocial issues.  asocial studies.1 aMcLean, Sarah J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965966zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520965966.jpg  a978-3-11-066755-4 UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA